[30;1m226 | [0m[35m    Pubs and Subs use the central scheduler to find each other, but not to[0m
[30;1m227 | [0m[35m    mediate the communication.  This means that there is very little additional[0m
[30;1m228 | [0m[35m    latency or overhead, and they are appropriate for very frequent data[0m
[30;1m229 | [0m[35m    transfers.  For context, most data transfer first checks with the scheduler to find which[0m
[30;1m230 | [0m[35m    workers should participate, and then does direct worker-to-worker[0m
[30;1m231 | [0m[35m    transfers.  This checking in with the scheduler provides some stability[0m
[30;1m232 | [0m[35m    guarantees, but also adds in a few extra network hops.  PubSub doesn't do[0m

[30;1m225 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m226 | [0m[35m    Pubs and Subs use the central scheduler to find each other, but not to[0m
[30;1m227 | [0m[35m    mediate the communication.  This means that there is very little additional[0m
[30;1m228 | [0m[35m    latency or overhead, and they are appropriate for very frequent data[0m
[30;1m229 | [0m[35m    transfers.  For context, most data transfer first checks with the scheduler to find which[0m

   Pattern: [32m.hostname[0m
[30;1m77 | [0m[35mDask always verifies the certificate presented by a remote endpoint[0m
[30;1m78 | [0m[35magainst the configured CA certificate(s).  Certificates are verified[0m
[30;1m79 | [0m[35mfor both "client" and "server" endpoints (in the TCP sense), ensuring[0m
[30;1m80 | [0m[35mthe endpoints are mutually authenticated.  The hostname or IP address for[0m
[30;1m81 | [0m[35mwhich a certificate has been issued is not checked; this should not be an[0m

[30;1m36 | [0m[35mclass ActiveMemoryManagerExtension:[0m
[30;1m37 | [0m[35m    """Scheduler extension that optimizes memory usage across the cluster.[0m
[30;1m38 | [0m[35m    It can be either triggered by hand or automatically every few seconds; at every[0m

[30;1m40 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m41 | [0m[35m    - create new replicas of in-memory tasks[0m

[30;1m14 | [0m[35msituations.  These are extensible to allow users to control in sensitive[0m

[30;1m156 | [0m[35mClient references[0m
[30;1m157 | [0m[35m-----------------[0m
[30;1m158 | [0m[35mFutures live on the cluster for as long as at least one Client holds a reference to[0m
[30;1m159 | [0m[35mthem. When the last Client holding a reference is shut down or crashes, then everything[0m
[30;1m160 | [0m[35mthat was referenced exclusively by it is pruned from the cluster. This is generally[0m
[30;1m161 | [0m[35mdesirable to prevent unclean client shutdowns from polluting the memory of long-running[0m

[30;1m6862 | [0m[35m        #. Find the mean occupancy of the cluster, defined as data managed by dask +[0m
[30;1m6863 | [0m[35m           unmanaged process memory that has been there for at least 30 seconds[0m
[30;1m6864 | [0m[35m           (``distributed.worker.memory.recent-to-old-time``).[0m
[30;1m6865 | [0m[35m           This lets us ignore temporary spikes caused by task heap usage.[0m

[30;1m169 | [0m[35mmemory management system. Upon `free`_, memory can remain allocated in user space and[0m
[30;1m170 | [0m[35mpotentially reusable by the next `malloc`_ - which in turn won't require a kernel call[0m
[30;1m171 | [0m[35meither. This is generally very desirable for C/C++ applications which have no memory[0m
[30;1m172 | [0m[35mallocator of their own, as it can drastically boost performance at the cost of a larger[0m
[30;1m173 | [0m[35mmemory footprint. CPython however adds its own memory allocator on top, which reduces[0m
[30;1m174 | [0m[35mthe need for this additional abstraction (with caveats).[0m
[30;1m175 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m59 | [0m[35m-----------[0m

[30;1m166 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m167 | [0m[35mMore in detail: both the Linux and MacOS memory allocators try to avoid performing a[0m
[30;1m168 | [0m[35m`brk`_ kernel call every time the application calls `free`_ by implementing a user-space[0m
[30;1m169 | [0m[35mmemory management system. Upon `free`_, memory can remain allocated in user space and[0m
[30;1m170 | [0m[35mpotentially reusable by the next `malloc`_ - which in turn won't require a kernel call[0m
[30;1m171 | [0m[35meither. This is generally very desirable for C/C++ applications which have no memory[0m

[30;1m50 | [0m[35mPause worker[0m
[30;1m51 | [0m[35m------------[0m
[30;1m52 | [0m[35mAt 80% :ref:`process memory <memtypes>` load, the worker's thread pool will stop[0m
[30;1m53 | [0m[35mstarting computation on additional tasks in the worker's queue. This gives time for the[0m
[30;1m54 | [0m[35mwrite-to-disk functionality to take effect even in the face of rapidly accumulating[0m
[30;1m55 | [0m[35mdata. Currently executing tasks continue to run. Additionally, data transfers to/from[0m
[30;1m56 | [0m[35mother workers are throttled to a bare minimum.[0m

[30;1m53 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m148 | [0m[35mlarger datasets in a more natural manner.  IPython parallel does not provide a[0m
[30;1m149 | [0m[35mmechanism for workers to communicate with each other, except by using the[0m
[30;1m150 | [0m[35mcentral node as an intermediary for data transfer or by relying on some other[0m
[30;1m151 | [0m[35mmedium, like a shared file system.  Data transfer through the central node can[0m
[30;1m152 | [0m[35measily become a bottleneck and so IPython parallel has been mostly helpful in[0m
[30;1m153 | [0m[35membarrassingly parallel work (the bulk of applications) but has not been used[0m
[30;1m154 | [0m[35mextensively for more sophisticated algorithms that require non-trivial[0m

[30;1m147 | [0m[35m``distributed`` to be more effective for more complex algorithms and to manage[0m
[30;1m148 | [0m[35mlarger datasets in a more natural manner.  IPython parallel does not provide a[0m
[30;1m149 | [0m[35mmechanism for workers to communicate with each other, except by using the[0m
[30;1m150 | [0m[35mcentral node as an intermediary for data transfer or by relying on some other[0m
[30;1m151 | [0m[35mmedium, like a shared file system.  Data transfer through the central node can[0m
[30;1m152 | [0m[35measily become a bottleneck and so IPython parallel has been mostly helpful in[0m
[30;1m153 | [0m[35membarrassingly parallel work (the bulk of applications) but has not been used[0m

[30;1m81 | [0m[35mBy default a single ``Worker`` runs many computations in parallel using as many[0m
[30;1m82 | [0m[35mthreads as your compute node has cores.  When using pure Python functions[0m
[30;1m83 | [0m[35mthis may not be optimal and you may instead want to run several separate[0m
[30;1m84 | [0m[35mworker processes on each node, each using one thread.  When configuring your[0m

[30;1m74 | [0m[35mthe non-blocking asynchronous model within Tornado allows us to run a[0m
[30;1m75 | [0m[35mscheduler, multiple workers, and multiple clients all within a single thread.[0m
[30;1m76 | [0m[35mThis gives us predictable performance, clean shutdowns, and the ability to drop[0m
[30;1m77 | [0m[35minto any point of the code during execution.[0m

[30;1m46 | [0m[35m-------[0m
[30;1m47 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m48 | [0m[35mDask.distributed is a Tornado TCP application.  Tornado provides us with both a[0m
[30;1m49 | [0m[35mcommunication layer on top of sockets, as well as a syntax for writing[0m
[30;1m50 | [0m[35masynchronous coroutines, similar to asyncio.  You can make modest changes to[0m
[30;1m51 | [0m[35mthe policies within this library without understanding much about Tornado,[0m
[30;1m52 | [0m[35mhowever moderate changes will probably require you to understand Tornado[0m

[30;1m14 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m15 | [0m[35mDask assigns tasks to workers following criteria of CPU occupancy, :doc:`resources`, and[0m
[30;1m16 | [0m[35mlocality. In the trivial use case of tasks that are not connected to each other, take[0m
[30;1m17 | [0m[35mthe same time to compute, return data of the same size, and have no resource[0m
[30;1m18 | [0m[35mconstraints, one will observe a perfect balance in memory occupation across workers too.[0m
[30;1m19 | [0m[35mIn all other use cases, however, as the computation goes it could cause an imbalance in[0m
[30;1m20 | [0m[35mmemory usage.[0m

[30;1m271 | [0m[35mThis transition function finds the appropriate path from the current to the[0m
[30;1m272 | [0m[35mfinal state.  It also serves as a central point for logging and diagnostics.[0m
[30;1m273 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m274 | [0m[35mOften we want to enact several transitions at once or want to continually[0m
[30;1m275 | [0m[35mrespond to new transitions recommended by initial transitions until we reach a[0m
[30;1m276 | [0m[35msteady state.  For that we use the ``transitions`` function (note the plural ``s``).[0m
[30;1m277 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m297 | [0m[35m**A common real-life use case**[0m
[30;1m298 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m299 | [0m[35m1. There are at least two workers on the cluster, A and B.[0m
[30;1m300 | [0m[35m2. Task x is computed successfully on worker A.[0m
[30;1m301 | [0m[35m3. When task x transitions to memory on worker A, the scheduler asks worker B to compute[0m
[30;1m302 | [0m[35m   task y, which depends on task x.[0m

[30;1m282 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m283 | [0m[35mFinally, the scheduler can change its mind multiple times over the lifetime of the task,[0m
[30;1m284 | [0m[35mso a ``resumed(executing->fetch)`` or ``resumed(long-running->fetch)`` task may be[0m
[30;1m285 | [0m[35mrequested to transition to ``waiting`` again, at which point it will just revert to its[0m
[30;1m286 | [0m[35m:attr:`~TaskState.previous` state and forget the whole incident; likewise a[0m
[30;1m287 | [0m[35m``resumed(flight->waiting)`` task could be requested to transition to ``fetch`` again,[0m
[30;1m288 | [0m[35mso it will just transition to ``flight`` instead.[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m1291[0m[34m of [0m[33m1944[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m234 | [0m[35m- The scheduler switches back to its original request:[0m
[30;1m235 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m236 | [0m[35m  - The scheduler asks the Worker to fetch a task that is currently[0m
[30;1m237 | [0m[35m    ``cancelled(flight)``; at which point the task will immediately revert to[0m
[30;1m238 | [0m[35m    ``flight``, forget that cancellation ever happened, and continue waiting on the data[0m
[30;1m239 | [0m[35m    fetch that's already running;[0m
[30;1m240 | [0m[35m  - The scheduler asks the Worker to compute a task that is currently[0m

[30;1m146 | [0m[35m(see :doc:`Tasks launching tasks <task-launch>`), at which point it secedes from the[0m
[30;1m147 | [0m[35mthread pool and changes state to `long-running`. ``executing`` and ``long-running`` are[0m
[30;1m148 | [0m[35malmost identical states, the only difference being that the latter don't count towards[0m
[30;1m149 | [0m[35mthe maximum number of tasks running in parallel at the same time.[0m
[30;1m150 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m151 | [0m[35mA task can terminate in three ways:[0m
[30;1m152 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m146 | [0m[35m(see :doc:`Tasks launching tasks <task-launch>`), at which point it secedes from the[0m

[30;1m71 | [0m[35mActors side-step both of these limitations:[0m
[30;1m72 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m73 | [0m[35m1.  **State**: Actors can hold on to and mutate state.  They are allowed to[0m
[30;1m74 | [0m[35m    update their state in-place.[0m
[30;1m75 | [0m[35m2.  **Overhead**: Operations on actors do not inform the central scheduler, and[0m
[30;1m76 | [0m[35m    so do not contribute to the 4000 task/second overhead.  They also avoid an[0m
[30;1m77 | [0m[35m    extra network hop and so have lower latencies.[0m

[30;1m163 | [0m[35mLast in, first out[0m
[30;1m164 | [0m[35m~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~[0m
[30;1m165 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m166 | [0m[35mWhen a worker finishes a task, the immediate dependencies of that task get top[0m
[30;1m167 | [0m[35mpriority.  This encourages a behavior of finishing ongoing work immediately[0m
[30;1m168 | [0m[35mbefore starting new work (depth-first graph traversal). This often conflicts with[0m
[30;1m169 | [0m[35mthe first-come-first-served objective, but often results in significantly reduced[0m
[30;1m170 | [0m[35mmemory footprints and, due to avoiding data spillage to disk, better overall runtimes.[0m

[30;1m99 | [0m[35mThis allows you to publish views on data that do not permanently take up[0m
[30;1m100 | [0m[35mcluster memory but can be surprising if you expect "publishing" to[0m
[30;1m101 | [0m[35mautomatically make a computed dataset rapidly available.[0m
[30;1m102 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m103 | [0m[35mAny client can publish or unpublish a dataset.[0m
